959. Dev Med Child Neurol. 1998 Jun;40(6):369-75.

Life expectancy of adults with cerebral palsy.

Strauss D(1), Shavelle R.

Author information:
(1)Department of Statistics, University of California, Riverside 92521, USA.

Comment in
    Dev Med Child Neurol. 2001 Aug;43(8):574.
    Dev Med Child Neurol. 2008 Jul;50(7):487-93.

To determine the predictors of mortality and find the life expectancies of 
adults with cerebral palsy (CP), data on 24,768 individuals aged 15 years and 
over who received services in California between January 1980 and December 1995 
were analyzed. Multivariate statistical methods to identify mortality 
predictors, and actuarial methods to determine corresponding life expectancies 
were used. The key predictors were lack of basic functional skills: mobility and 
feeding. Adults lacking these skills had much reduced life expectancies, as 
short as 11 years for the worst functioning groups. By contrast, survival of 
high-functioning adults was close to that of the general population. The 
influence on survival of cognitive skills, type of CP, and other factors appears 
to be expressed largely through their effect on basic functioning. Life 
expectancies of adults of a given age can differ by 40 years or more, according 
to their functional level.

